# 🧠 LAB REPO — Copilot Instructions

## Purpose
This repository is an experimental and execution environment for:
- Prompts
- Agents
- MCP tools
- AI workflows
- Prototypes
- Automation scripts

This is NOT a production application repo.

---

## 🧱 Core Principles

- Prefer clarity over cleverness
- Keep outputs modular and reusable
- All logic must be portable to other repos (core/, services/, data/)
- Avoid tight coupling between experiments
- Every artifact should be self-contained

---

## 📂 Folder Responsibilities

### /prompts
- Task-specific prompts
- Must be reusable and parameterized
- Avoid hardcoding project-specific data

### /agents
- Structured AI agents (Copilot, OpenAI, MCP)
- Include:
  - Role definition
  - Capabilities
  - Inputs / Outputs
  - Execution flow

### /mcp
- Machine Control Protocol tools
- Define:
  - Tool name
  - Input schema
  - Output schema
  - Execution logic

### /experiments
- Temporary or exploratory work
- Can be unstable
- Must include short README explaining purpose

### /prototypes
- Semi-stable implementations
- Should be promotable to services/ or core/

### /copilot
- Copilot-specific agents, prompts, and behaviors

---

## 🧠 Coding Standards

### General
- Use clear, readable structure
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions
- Prefer functional patterns over complex class hierarchies

### JavaScript / TypeScript
- Use modern ES modules
- Prefer async/await
- Keep functions small and composable

### Python
- Use clear function-based structure
- Avoid overengineering
- Keep scripts runnable as standalone modules

### Markdown
- Use clean formatting
- No excessive spacing
- Use headers and bullet lists
- Prefer structured templates

---

## 🤖 Agent Design Rules

All agents must include:

- Name
- Purpose
- Inputs
- Outputs
- Step-by-step execution logic
- Example usage

Agents should:
- Be deterministic when possible
- Avoid vague instructions
- Be reusable across projects

---

## 🔌 MCP Tool Rules

Each MCP tool must define:

- Tool name
- Description
- Input schema (JSON)
- Output schema (JSON)
- Execution steps

Keep tools:
- Focused on one responsibility
- Stateless where possible
- Easy to integrate into pipelines

---

## 🧪 Experiment Rules

- Experiments must be isolated
- No shared hidden dependencies
- Include a short README:
  - What it does
  - Why it exists
  - Next step (keep, refactor, delete)

---

## 🔄 Promotion Path

Artifacts move like this:

lab/experiment → lab/prototype → services/ or core/

Do NOT leave important logic stuck in experiments.

---

## ⚠️ Anti-Patterns (Avoid)

- Mixing production code with experiments
- Hardcoding credentials or environment data
- Creating large monolithic scripts
- Vague or unstructured prompts
- Duplicate logic across folders

---

## 🚀 Output Expectations

When generating code or content:

- Be structured and production-aware
- Include minimal but clear comments
- Prefer reusable patterns
- Assume code may be promoted to production

---

## 🧩 Integration Awareness

Lab outputs should be compatible with:

- FastAPI (backend)
- React + TypeScript (frontend)
- PostgreSQL (data layer)
- GraphQL (API layer)

---

## 🧠 Default Behavior for Copilot

When unsure:

1. Choose simplicity
2. Prefer modular output
3. Add structure over verbosity
4. Make outputs reusable
5. Assume this will scale later

---

## 🏁 Goal

Turn ideas into structured, testable, and promotable building blocks for the ecosystem.
